00:38:57,710 --> 00:39:04,990
do if you're a modern tester is show a better way forward than falling back to the old ways.

666
00:39:05,630 --> 00:39:12,430
Which means that the big essence of this principle is that you constantly need to be

667
00:39:12,430 --> 00:39:14,030
looking at the system, take a step back.

668
00:39:14,030 --> 00:39:14,590
Yep.

669
00:39:14,750 --> 00:39:21,630
Because you may – it's very possible and very common you may be focusing on the wrong bottleneck.

670
00:39:22,370 --> 00:39:25,490
So, stop and ask yourself, is this the right bottleneck?

671
00:39:25,490 --> 00:39:26,050
Back up.

672
00:39:26,050 --> 00:39:28,210
Look, is this really the slowdown in the system?

673
00:39:28,210 --> 00:39:29,570
Does it exist somewhere else?

674
00:39:29,570 --> 00:39:31,490
Have I already mitigated this bottleneck?

675
00:39:31,490 --> 00:39:33,170
What is the largest one in the system?

676
00:39:33,170 --> 00:39:34,130
Dive back in.

677
00:39:34,130 --> 00:39:35,570
It's really easy to get stuck.

678
00:39:35,570 --> 00:39:38,530
What is creating risk to the system?

679
00:39:38,530 --> 00:39:43,730
That's something test is very good at, although they don't think of it that way.

680
00:39:43,730 --> 00:39:45,010
What is creating risk?

681
00:39:46,690 --> 00:39:48,770
I've talked about it a million times before.

682
00:39:48,770 --> 00:39:49,490
I hate Scrum.

683
00:39:52,160 --> 00:39:58,000
It doesn't take long going through Scrum to realize when all of the bugs are created.

684
00:39:59,520 --> 00:40:04,240
It's at 11 p.m. the night before the sprint in demo.

685
00:40:04,240 --> 00:40:05,040
Yes.

686
00:40:05,040 --> 00:40:06,800
Almost all of the time.

687
00:40:07,790 --> 00:40:13,120
And when you shift to a Kanban model –

